# Extern & Multilevel File Programming - Part 2

---

## 1. Declarations vs. Definitions: The Fundamental Rule

When dealing with global variables and multiple functions, understanding **how many times** you can declare a variable is key.

### The Golden Rules

| Type | Allowed Count | Purpose |
|------|---------------|---------|
| **Declaration** (using `extern`) | Any number of times | Tells compiler variable exists |
| **Definition** (allocates memory) | **Only ONCE** | Creates the variable in memory |

---

### Multiple Declarations

A **declaration** (using `extern`) can be written **any number of times** in a program.

```c
void func1() {
    extern int g;  // Declaration 1
    printf("%d", g);
}

void func2() {
    extern int g;  // Declaration 2 (same variable)
    printf("%d", g);
}

void func3() {
    extern int g;  // Declaration 3 (same variable)
    printf("%d", g);
}

int g = 10;  // Definition (only once!)
```

**Valid**: Multiple declarations referring to the same definition.

---

### Single Definition

A **definition** (which allocates memory) must be written **only once**.

#### ❌ Invalid: Multiple Definitions

```c
int g = 10;  // Definition 1

void main() {
    printf("%d", g);
}

int g = 20;  // ❌ ERROR: Definition 2 (duplicate)
```

**Error**: `Redeclaration of 'g'` or `Multiple definition of 'g'`

---

### Global Declaration

Instead of declaring a variable inside **every function**, you can place a **single declaration** outside of all functions to make it a **global declaration**.

#### Before: Declaration in Each Function

```c
void func1() {
    extern int g;  // Declaration
    printf("%d", g);
}

void func2() {
    extern int g;  // Declaration (repeated)
    printf("%d", g);
}

void func3() {
    extern int g;  // Declaration (repeated)
    printf("%d", g);
}

int g = 10;  // Definition
```

---

#### After: Global Declaration (Better)

```c
extern int g;  // ✅ Global declaration (accessible to all functions)

void func1() {
    printf("%d", g);  // No need for extern here
}

void func2() {
    printf("%d", g);  // No need for extern here
}

void func3() {
    printf("%d", g);  // No need for extern here
}

int g = 10;  // Definition
```

**Benefit**: Cleaner code, no repetition.

