## 2. Multi-File Application Architecture

In C, a **"program"** typically refers to the final **executable file** (e.g., `sample.exe` in Windows or `.out` in Linux).

### Life and Scope

The **life** and **scope** of an `extern` variable span the **entire program**, meaning it can be accessed across **all `.c` files** that make up the executable.

```
┌────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│             ENTIRE PROGRAM                     │
│                                                │
│  ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────┐   │
│  │ File A.c │  │ File B.c │  │ File C.c │   │
│  │          │  │          │  │          │   │
│  │ int g=10;│  │extern g; │  │extern g; │   │
│  │ (defin.) │  │ (declar.)│  │ (declar.)│   │
│  └──────────┘  └──────────┘  └──────────┘   │
│                                                │
│  All files share the SAME 'g'                 │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

---

### Independent Compilation

The **compiler** treats every `.c` file as an **individual unit**. When compiling `File_B.c`, the compiler has **no knowledge** of variables defined in `File_A.c`.

```
File_A.c ──→ Compiler ──→ A.obj  (knows only A.c)
File_B.c ──→ Compiler ──→ B.obj  (knows only B.c)
                │
                └─→ Linker ──→ program.exe (combines both)
```

**Key Point**: Each file is compiled **independently**.

